{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569869"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:34:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.08,0.28,0.3,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13199"},{"type":"tags","id":"13200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40948"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for cardiovascular risk assessment. He has type 2 diabetes diagnosed at 35 years with a recent HbA1c of 9.5%. He has atrial fibrillation managed with amiodarone and apixaban. He smokes 15 cigarettes per day and has done so for 30 years. He takes metformin and metoprolol. He works as a truck driver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min and irregularly irregular, blood pressure 128/80 mmHg. His height is 170cm, weight 120 kg and BMI 41 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol 5.2 mmol/L (3.0-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL 1.1 mmol/L (0.9-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDL 3.4 mmol/L (2.0-3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriglycerides 1.5 mmol/L (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 55 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary ACR 2.5 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis calculated 5-year cardiovascular risk is 17%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lifestyle modification and reassessment in 12 months","Commence aspirin","Commence statin therapy only","Commence antihypertensive and statin therapy","Commence antihypertensive therapy only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a high absolute cardiovascular risk (\u0026gt;10% over five years) based on the Australian cardiovascular risk calculator. The presence of poorly controlled diabetes, smoking, obesity, and atrial fibrillation significantly contribute to his risk, despite his normal blood cholesterol levels and blood pressure readings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence antihypertensive and statin therapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate management. Current guidelines recommend both blood pressure lowering and statin therapy for all patients at high cardiovascular risk, regardless of blood pressure or cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing statin therapy only \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Eantihypertensive therapy only \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be incomplete management given his high cardiovascular risk status requires both medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modification alone with reassessment\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient given this patient\u0027s high risk status and need for anticoagulation. While lifestyle changes (smoking cessation, dietary modification, exercise) are essential, they should be implemented alongside pharmacological therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it is neither adequate for stroke prevention in atrial fibrillation nor routinely recommended for primary cardiovascular prevention. The ASPREE trial demonstrated that the risks of major bleeding with aspirin outweighed the cardiovascular benefits in primary prevention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High absolute cardiovascular risk (\u003E10%) requires both blood pressure lowering and statin therapy regardless of blood pressure or cholesterol levels.","Aspirin is no longer routinely recommended for primary cardiovascular prevention based on evidence from the ASPREE trial."],"references":["Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator. In: National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","McNeil JJ, Nelson MR, Woods RL, Lockery JE, et al. Effect of aspirin on all-cause mortality in the healthy elderly. New England Journal of Medicine. 2018;379:1519-28. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1803955"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}